      <h2>The Bottom Line: Lighting Is a Safety System</h2>
      <p>Treating job site lighting as just another tool rather than a critical safety system is a mistake that costs contractors in OSHA fines, injury claims, and lost productivity. The investment in proper lighting — including cool-running LED technology, adequate coverage, battery backup, and weather-appropriate fixtures — is one of the most cost-effective safety improvements you can make.</p>
      <p>A complete job site safety lighting kit doesn't have to be expensive. A setup with two 50W LED floodlights (4.8★) for task areas, a 100FT string light (4.7★) for walkway coverage, and a battery-powered DEWALT DCL079B (4.8★) for backup gives you comprehensive safety coverage for under $300 total. Compare that to the cost of a single trip-and-fall injury claim — which averages $40,000 — and the return on investment is undeniable.</p>
      <p>Light your site like someone's life depends on it. Because on a construction site, it often does.</p>

